passages.text: August 28, 2025 03:02 AM GMT

KSS reported solid 2Q results with values / GM in- line and adj EBITDA beat. Notably, the company reported flat comp sales in July. Guidance for FY25 was raised for sales and overall profitability but revised lower for gross margin. The equity is \(+24\%\) and bonds +5pt as of market close, 08/27.

- Flat comp sales in July was a key positive supported by the expansion of coupon eligible brands, with management noting strong trends continuing into August for back-to-school.- Kohl's revised sales guidance to the high end and gross margin to the low end of their prior ranges, reflecting tariff headwinds in 2H.- Management is focused on expanding PL offerings and coupon-eligible brands to cater to a value-oriented consumer.- The company is on track to pay down the revolver as guided during the new issue offering and extended its maturity runway by successfully refinancing its 2025 notes.- Following the rally post results, we close our buy recommendation on KSS '31s and '45s. Despite a strong 2Q, the credit still faces structural and cyclical concerns heading into 2H and FY26.
MORGAN STANLEY & CO. LLC

Morgan Stanley does and seeks to do business with companies covered in Morgan Stanley Research. Exhibit 1: Kohl's market levels and total returns (as of 08/27/2025)

Credit View \((=):\) KSS bonds rallied post 2Q- results with the '31s and '4Ssp up- \$5pts. Following the strong performance we are closing out our trade and moving to neutral on KSS bonds. The '31s and the '4S5s have both significantly outperformed the HY Retail index MTD with returns of \(11.1\%\) and \(11.9\%\) respectively, with the '31s also outperforming YTD. We continue to appreciate Kohl's stronger credit profile among the 'stressed- yielding' cohort that includes the likes of MIK, HOME, SAGLEN, LINTA and SPLS, given leverage \(

- Accessories outperformed, led by jewelry (+12%) & impulse purchases (+30%), driving positive comp sales for the segment excluding Sephora (+3% YoY, flat comp sales).- Footwear slightly underperformed due to softness in sandals and active styles, offset by strong dress casual and kids' footwear; Home business performed well in décor, bedding, and bath, partially offset by softness in small electronics.- Positive performance from new and non-Kohl's card customers vs core customer segment (Kohl's card customers) seeing low-teens declines.- Management noted lower-to-middle income consumers remain most pressured, while higher-income customers are more resilient.- Strategic emphasis on expanding PL and coupon-eligible brands to support value-oriented consumer, as well as re-balancing assortment, and enhancing omnichannel shopping experience.- Gross margin guidance was revised to the lower end of the prior 30-50bp range, primarily to reflect headwinds from tariffs expected to impact the back half of the year.- Inventory was -5% YoY and management expects a MSD decline in inventory YoY for FY25.- Back-to-school trends in August showed strength, particularly in backpacks, kids footwear, fleece, and denim, in proprietary and national brands (e.g., Lauren Conrad, Nine West, Levi's, Nike).- Kohl's reduced the outstanding balance on its revolver and continues to expect the revolver to be fully paid down by year-end.- Kohl's successfully refinanced July 2025 maturities, issuing \(360m\) of 10% senior secured notes due 2030, extending maturity runway to until 2029.- Kohl's recognized a \(129m\) benefit from a credit card lawsuit settlement during the quarter, excluded from adj metrics.

Operating results (+): KSS reported 2Q net sales of \(3.35bn, - 5.1\%\) YoY and comp sales \(- 4.2\%\) , consistent with our estimate of \(3.35bn\) and slightly ahead of cons. estimate of \(3.31bn\) . The decline in Q2 sales was primarily driven by fewer transactions, specifically in stores. KSS reported other revenue (CC business) of \(199mn\) in 2Q, a \(- 4\%\) YoY.

We calculate adjusted EBITDA of \(\) 344m\(, - 4.4\%\) YoY, which beat our estimate of \(\) 304m\(and consensus'\) 307m\(en estimate. Gross margin expanded +28bp YoY to 39.9%, in - line with the Street's expectation, led by category mix benefits, outperformance in private label, and inventory management. SG&A was - 4.1% YoY but increased 32bp YoY as a \% of sales to 33.8\%. SG&A benefited from lower spending in stores, marketing, and a portion of credit expenses shifting into other revenue.

Guidance (+): The company raised its prior FY25 guide, with key components including: (1) Net sales - 5% to - 6% (vs - 5% to - 7% prior); (2) Comp sales - 4% to - 5% (vs - 4% to - 6% prior); (3) Gross Margin expansion of - 30bp (vs 30- 50bp prior); (4) SG&A - 4% to - 4.5% (vs - 3.5% to - 5% prior) (5) Operating margin of 2.5% to 2.7% (vs 2.2% to 2.6% prior); (6) Depreciation of \(\) 705m\( (vs\) \ \(730m\) prior); (7) Interest expense of \(\) 305m\( (vs\) \ \(315m\) prior); (8) Adj EPS \(\) 0.5\(to\) \ \(0.8\) (vs \(\) 0.10\(to\) \ \(0.60\) prior); (9) Capex - \(\) 400\(- \) 425m\(prior).
Balance Sheet (+): Inventories ended the quarter - 5% YoY at \(\) 3bn\(. Total liquidity ended

the quarter at \(\) 1.6\(bn inclusive of\) \ \(174\) mn of cash on the balance sheet and \(\) 1.43\(mn undrawn under the revolver. The company reported quarter - end net - adjusted leverage of\) 2.6x.
